Complementary information and requirements:

- A Guide to Convolutional Neural Networks for Computer Vision ( https://sci-hub.tw/10.2200/s00822ed1v01y201712cov015 )
- Going deeper in the automated identification of Herbarium specimens ( https://link.springer.com/article/10.1186/s12862-017-1014-z )
- Taxon and trait recognition from digitized herbarium specimens using deep convolutional neural networks ( https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/23818107.2018.1446357?journalCode=tabg21 )
- Applications of deep convolutional neural networks to digitized natural history collections ( https://bdj.pensoft.net/article/21139/ )
- Attention Augmented Convolutional Networks ( https://arxiv.org/abs/1904.09925 );
- Encoder-Decoder with Atrous Separable Convolution for Semantic Image Segmentation ( https://arxiv.org/pdf/1802.02611v3.pdf );
- Semi‐automated workflows for acquiring specimen data from label images in herbarium collections ( https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/tax.596014 );
- The use of Optical Character Recognition (OCR) in the digitisation of herbarium specimen labels ( https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4086207/ );
- Toward a large‐scale and deep phenological stage annotation of herbarium specimens: Case studies from temperate, tropical, and equatorial floras ( https://europepmc.org/articles/pmc6426157 );

objectives:
Hundreds of herbarium collections, currently in Natural History Museums and other similar institutions, have accumulated a valuable heritage and knowledge of plants over several centuries. Recent initiatives started ambitious preservation plans to digitize this information and make it available to botanists and the general public through web portals. However, thousands of sheets are still unidentified at the species level while numerous sheets should be reviewed and updated following more recent taxonomic knowledge. Computer vision and machine learning approaches applied to herbarium sheets are promising, but recent methods based on deep neural networks are still not well studied in this particular problem domain, in comparison to other areas.

This project will explore and evaluate the accuracy with which deep learning technology can be potentially exploited for the processing of herbarium images, specifically envisioning (a) species identification, and (b) the extraction of other metadata elements for supporting the indexing of herbarium images. Particular attention will be given to the processing of the labels typically present within these images, containing hand-written and/or typewritten information on collector names, the date and location of collection, and species identification. 

Objectives:

- Study of state-of-the-art computer vision methods, based on deep neural networks, for image segmentation and classification;
- Development and evaluation of methods for segmenting labels within herbarium images;
- Development and evaluation of methods for extracting metadata elements (e.g., collection dates) from the labels within herbarium images;
- Development and evaluation of methods for species identification, leveraging the entire herbarium images;

References:

- A benchmark dataset of herbarium specimen images with label data ( https://bdj.pensoft.net/article/31817/ );

