This proposal is within the field of human-computer interaction and physical rehabilitation.

Each year, approximately 1 million people suffer a Cerebral Vascular Accident in Europe alone, making stroke on the biggest burdens to health and social care. Improving the quality and efficiency of rehabilitation programs is one of the fundamental strategies for a better and cost-effective healthcare system.

Stroke is a condition caused by a disturbance of blood supply to the brain, which results in the death of a localized area of brain cells. Such an event can have a significant impact on cognitive and motor abilities. Stroke impacts primarily one side of the body (i.e. hemiparesis), while leaving the other side mostly unaffected. In practice, stroke survivors’ brains “forget” how to correctly perform body movements, particularly upper-body movements (e.g. handshake, comb hair, wave, etc.) as the cells responsible for motor control/coordination died. Rehabilitation aims to re-teach these functional movements to stroke survivors.

Interactive technologies have the potential to play a major role in this process making it more engaging and effective; however, they are usually built for a stereotypical patient without taking into account the needs of stroke survivors, stroke rehabilitation practices, and physiotherapists’ needs. 

First, the motor abilities of stroke survivors are highly heterogeneous, which requires a tool that can offer highly customizable upper limb activities. Second, stroke survivors tend to develop compensatory movements, which is a natural reaction to the inability to fully control their upper body movements. For example, in performing a handshake, survivors can develop altered should movement patterns to compensate for limited reach. While compensatory movements help people to achieve their task, it can also be detrimental to the recovery process and induce new problems. Thus, stroke rehabilitation practices aim to strike a balance between teaching movements with minimal compensations and regaining functional abilities. Third, while many rehabilitation systems have been proposed in the past, few are in use in today’s rehabilitation centres because they do not match the needs of professionals. Interactive rehabilitation systems often make use of motion tracking technologies such as accelerometers, depth cameras, marker-based systems, etc.; each of these is a compromise between accuracy and ease of use. For instance, Kinect cameras are “walk-up &amp; use sensors” that are able to capture gross movements but fail to quantify internal rotations or subtle motion. On the other hand, marker-based sensors require a setup time where users wear markers but can achieve sub-millimetric accuracy. Which of these is more appropriate to stroke rehabilitation depends on type of exercise, rehabilitation stage, and therapeutic goals.

In this work, you will design and develop a clinically relevant stroke rehabilitation tool that can be provide personalized activities, appropriate biofeedback, and use multiple tracking technologies. You will work in close collaboration with physiotherapist professionals that will help you co-design such solution. 

In addition to your master thesis, you are expected to advance state of the art in the field of human-computer interaction and submit a paper to an international conference or journal.

Your tasks will include:
1) Literature review;
2) Get acquainted with interactive technologies and prototyping tools;
3) Design rehabilitation tool;
