objectives:
In archaeology, a typology is the result of the classification of things (e.g., fragments of pottery artifacts) according to their physical characteristics, helping to manage a large mass of archaeological data. The products of the classification, i.e. the classes, are also called types.

Specifically in the context of cultures that produced pottery, archaeologists invariably spend a great deal of time defining ceramic &#034;types.&#034; Each type is a series of attributes which distinguishes one group of pottery (whether whole vessels or potsherds) from all other groups, such that each type was produced in a single time and place. By sorting potsherds in terms of types, archaeologists can examine a series of potsherds (including those lying on a site surface) and quickly suggest when and where the pottery was made. By extension, they can estimate when a prehistoric site was used, whether there are any traded pieces, and so on.

The classification of pottery sherds into types is currently performed manually on large quantities of archaeological artifacts, leveraging the observation of physical attributes (a) in the sherds themselves, (b) in photos, or (c) in standardized black-and-white line drawings. This project will address the study and development of machine learning methods, leveraging deep neural networks, for automatic archaeological pottery sherd classification.

Objectives:
- Study of state-of-the-art methods for image classification, leveraging deep neural networks;
- Development and evaluation of a classification method for assigning standardized black-and-white line drawings to types.

References:
- Classifying and Visualising Roman Pottery using Computer-scanned Typologies ( http://intarch.ac.uk/journal/issue50/14/1.html );
- Automatic Classification of Archaeological Pottery Sherds ( https://www.iti.gr/iti/files/document/publications/ACM-daras.pdf );

