objectives:
Archival aerial photographs are a valuable source of information on the land cover. Unfortunately, these are single-channel, monochromatic data, which means that the interpretation possibilities of these data are significantly limited. Increase the visual quality of aerial images, by giving them colors similar to natural ones while maintaining or improving the level of detail, can have many practical applications.

For instance, colorizing and super-resolving grayscale aereal images can improve digital maps created from the original images (e.g., making the data easier to analyze with the human eye, and enabling the automation of the identification process and analysis of photographed objects), and it can also provide value by increasing the performance of object detection and semantic algorithms in historical aereal imagery (i.e., if a grayscale satellite image is colorized, then its potential value for use in machine learning algorithms increases).

This research project concerns the development of novel approaches based on deep learning (e.g., leveraging fully-convolutional neural networks together with adversarial training) for simultaneously colorising and super-resolving historical aerial photos. Experiments will leverage modern datasets (e.g., https://spacenetchallenge.github.io/datasets/datasetHomePage.html ), and we also envision a case study with Portuguese aerial photos from the 1950s.

Goals:

- Study state-of-the-art deep learning methods for image colorization and super-resolution;
- Development and evaluation of novel appraoches for coloriozing and/or super-resolving black-and-white aerial photographs;

References:

- Enhancement of spectral quality of archival aerial photographs using satellite imagery for detection of land cover ( https://doi.org/10.1117/1.JRS.11.036001 );
- Improvement of interpretability of archival aerial photographs using remote sensing tools ( https://doi.org/10.1117/12.2325813 );

