objectives:
Flooding is the world’s most costly type of natural disaster in terms of both economic losses and human causalities. A first and essential procedure towards flood monitoring is based on identifying areas afected by flooding, which gives authorities relevant regions to focus. This project envisions the development of a method/algorithm to identify regions affected by a flooding in aerial (e.g., satelite) images. For multiple instances of flooding events, taking as input aerial image patches covering a wide spatial area together with other types of remote sensing products for the same region (e.g., information on terrail elevation, slope, permiability, etc.), the method should produce segmentation masks of the flooded area. The percentage of correctly labeled pixels can be used as an evaluation criteria.

Goals:

• Study deep learning methods for image segmentation (e.g., based on fully-convolutional neural networks);
• Implement and evaluate a method for segmenting flooded areas in aerial imagery;

References:

- Exploiting ConvNet Diversity for Flooding Identification ( https://arxiv.org/pdf/1711.03564.pdf );

