objectives:
Develop, implement and test a Virtual Network Function Chaining using Segment Routing.

Network Function Virtualization (NFV) aims to bring flexibility and programmability to the network layers, enabling the replacement of traditional network appliances for software components, running in virtual servers. In particular, NFV decouples the network services from the underlying (dedicated) hardware infrastructure, enabling to design, manage and run complex network services on software, running in virtualized servers.On the other hand, Segment Routing (SR) is a new paradigm for routing in IPv6 and MPLS scenarios and relies on the source routing concept, where a source node adds to a packet an ordered sequence of segments that must be followed in order to the packet reach its final destination.  

The goal of this thesis is to test the implementation and deployment of NVF services chaining using Segment Routing and new paradigms on Network Softwarization and the SDN/NFV landscape. 

The work will comprise the following phases:

1.	Revision of the state of the art on NFV implementation and deployment;
2.	Revision of the state of the art on segment routing;
3.	Identification of test cases regarding NFV service chaining;
4.	Definition of the overall architecture;
5.	Implementation;
6.	Experimental evaluation;
7.	Discussion and conclusions.

This proposal is within the field of human-computer interaction and physical rehabilitation.

Improvements in healthcare mean that people live longer and survive many injuries. Still, increasing numbers of people need to undertake physiotherapy at some point in their lifetime, many during long periods of time. In physiotherapy sessions, the professional teaches and demonstrates exercises. A patient will then perform the exercise, and while they practice, the physiotherapist provides immediate feedback and correction to ensure the patient performs the exercise correctly. This feedback ensures the patient will be able to recover physical functioning and avoid re-aggravating their injury. In addition, the feedback can provide the patient with motivation to continue their exercises. 

The problem is that patients also need to perform these exercises without the guidance of a physiotherapist, either at home or because the physiotherapist is attending other patients. Without guidance, patients risk performing their exercises incorrectly—at best without gaining restorative benefits, and at worst re-injuring themselves.

Previous work has largely explored biofeedback techniques for 2D “canonical” movements but fail to guide patients in true 3D functional movements (e.g. drinking water, combing hair, handshake, and so forth).

In this work, you will design and develop new biofeedback techniques that are able to guide and correct patients during 3D functional upper-body movements. You will use VIVE’s motion tracking technologies and Unity 3D. You will work in close collaboration with physiotherapist professionals that will help you co-design such techniques.

Tasks that you will undertake include:
- Task 1 – Literature review;
- Task 2 – Get acquainted with prototyping tools and tracking technologies;
- Task 3 – Co-design biofeedback techniques;
- Task 4 – Develop biofeedback techniques;
- Task 5 – Evaluate techniques;
- Task 6 – Write master thesis.

In addition to your master thesis, you are expected to advance state of the art in the field of human-computer interaction and submit a paper to an international conference or journal.

A mobilidade nas grandes capitais europeias, incluindo Lisboa, ainda não é sustentável. A Câmara Municipal de Lisboa (CML) tem estabelecido esforços para a recolha de todos os dados de mobilidade disponíveis, incluindo dados de tráfego (rodovias, ferrovias, ciclovias, hidrovias e aerovias) e contexto situacional (eventos públicos, planeamento urbano, meteorologia, interdições). Apesar destes esforços, o potencial do conhecimento a extrair sobre estes dados é ainda desconhecido.

Inserida neste contexto, esta tese de mestrado visa:
1) integrar duas ou mais fontes heterogéneas de tráfego em áreas de interesse, incluindo estações de metro e/ou paragens de autocarro;
2) consolidar estas fontes com contexto situacional disponível;
3) explorar sinergias intermodais no tráfego urbano em diferentes pontos da cidade;
4) desenvolver algoritmos de descoberta eficiente de padrões multimodais de mobilidade urbana;
5) estudar correlações entre os padrões multimodais encontrados e o contexto situacional dos mesmos.

Neste trabalho pretende-se desenvolver uma maquete de uma pista para pequenos robots (veículos autónomos ou semi-autónomos) com características que permitam demonstrar as capacidades de comando e controlo dos robots.

O trabalho incluirá:
