objectives:
Tools for the automated or semi-automated analysis of text are increasingly being used in the social sciences, e.g. in the context of studies related to policy analysis, leveraging textual materials covering various administrative, legislative, and political aspects of policy processes. Initiatives such as the Comparative Agendas Project ( https://www.comparativeagendas.net ) or the The Manifesto Project ( https://manifesto-project.wzb.eu/ ) relly on manual coding to classify legislation and other relevant texts into major topics and subtopics, although several recent studies are increasingly using automated approaches to carry out this task. This projects will address the study and development of methods, based on deep neural networks, for annotating relevant sentences or quasi-sentences in textual materials related to policy processes (e.g., legislative contents or newspaper opinion articles) and for classifying the text spans  into the classes from standard codebooks regarding policy topics.

Goals: 

• Study recent neural network methods for natural language processing, specifically sequence tagging method for concept indentification and classification;
• Implementation and evaluation of models for classifying spans of text according to policy topics;

References:

• Text-as-Data Methods for Comparative Policy Analysis ( https://www.fabriziogilardi.org/resources/papers/Gilardi-Wueest-TextAsData-Policy-Analysis.pdf );

